SIMPLE: film
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Film
<hw>Film</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>film</ets>
skin, fr. <ets>fell</ets> skin; akin to <ets>fylmen</ets> membrane,
OFries. <ets>filmene</ets> skin. See <er>Fell</er> skin.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A thin skin; a pellicle; a membranous covering, causing
opacity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He from thick <qex>films</qex> shall purge the visual ray.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>hence, any thin layer covering a surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A slender thread, as that of a cobweb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her whip of cricket's bone, the lash of <qex>film</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>The layer, usually of gelatin
or collodion, containing the sensitive salts of photographic
plates.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>a flexible sheet of celluloid
or other plastic material to which a light-sensitive layer has been
applied, used for recording images by the processes of photography. It
is commonly used in rolls mounted within light-proof canisters suitable
for simple insertion into cameras designed for such canisters. On such
rolls, varying numbers of photographs may be taken before the canister
needs to be replaced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>a motion picture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>the art of making motion pictures; -- used mostly in
the phrase <it>the film</it>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>a thin transparent sheet of plastic, used for
wrapping objects; <as>as, polyethylene <ex>film</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Celluloid film</b></col> <fld>(Photog.)</fld>, <cd>a thin
flexible sheet of celluloid, coated with a sensitized emulsion of
gelatin, and used as a substitute for photographic plates.</cd> --
<col><b>Cut film</b></col> <fld>(Photog.)</fld>, <cd>a celluloid film
cut into pieces suitable for use in a camera.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Film</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Film
<hw>Film</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover with a thin
skin or pellicle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will but skin and <qex>film</qex> the ulcerous place.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to make a motion picture of (any event or literary
work); to record with a movie camera; <as>as, to <ex>film</ex> the
inauguration ceremony; to <ex>film</ex> Dostoevsky's Crime and
Punishment or Tolstoy's War and Peace</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>filmable</ent>⟦br⟧
